# 🏥 Lattice / OpenClaims — Complete Interview-Ready Guide

---

## 1. Project Overview

**What it does:** Lattice (also called OpenClaims) is an AI-powered medical document processing system. You upload a clinical PDF (like a hospital discharge summary, insurance claim form, or encounter report), and the system automatically:
1. Extracts raw text from the PDF using **AWS Textract** (OCR)
2. Sends that raw text to **OpenAI GPT-4o**, which extracts structured medical entities (patient info, encounters, claims, conditions, hospitals)
3. Stores the structured data in **PostgreSQL** (as JSON)
4. Builds a **knowledge graph** in **Neo4j** — connecting patients to their encounters, claims, conditions, and hospitals
5. Displays everything in a **React dashboard** with an interactive graph visualizer

**What problem it solves:** Medical documents are messy, unstructured PDFs. Hospitals, insurers, and healthcare analysts need this information in a structured, queryable format. Manually reading and entering data from PDFs is slow and error-prone. This system automates the entire pipeline from raw PDF → structured data → searchable knowledge graph.

**Why it exists:** Built for the **AWS AI for Bharat Hackathon** — a competition focused on using AI for Indian healthcare innovation. The goal was to demonstrate how AI + graph databases can create a "longitudinal patient record" from fragmented clinical documents.

---

## 2. Tech Stack & Imports

### Backend

| Library | What it is | Why it's here | What breaks without it |
|---------|-----------|---------------|----------------------|
| **FastAPI** | High-performance async Python web framework | Handles all REST API endpoints (upload, list, graph queries). Chosen over Flask/Django for native async support and auto-generated Swagger docs | No API server at all |
| **SQLAlchemy** | Python ORM (Object-Relational Mapper) | Maps Python classes to PostgreSQL tables so we write Python, not raw SQL | Cannot store/query documents or patients in Postgres |
| **Alembic** | Database migration tool for SQLAlchemy | Manages schema changes (adding columns, tables) without losing data | Have to manually alter database tables |
| **Pydantic** | Data validation library | Validates all API inputs/outputs AND validates the structured data GPT-4o returns | Invalid data would silently pass through; no schema enforcement |
| **pydantic-settings** | Env variable loader for Pydantic | Loads [.env](file:///Users/khatriaryan/Desktop/Lattice/.env) file values into a typed [Settings](file:///Users/khatriaryan/Desktop/Lattice/backend/app/config.py#4-27) object | Config values wouldn't load from environment |
| **Celery** | Distributed task queue | Runs document processing asynchronously (upload returns immediately, processing happens in background) | Uploads would block the API; user waits minutes per upload |
| **Redis** | In-memory data store | Acts as the message broker for Celery (holds the "process this document" messages) | Celery can't receive or send tasks |
| **Neo4j Python Driver** | Official Neo4j database driver | Connects to Neo4j graph database, runs Cypher queries | No knowledge graph functionality |
| **OpenAI Python SDK** | Official OpenAI API client | Calls GPT-4o for structured medical data extraction | No AI extraction — the core feature breaks |
| **Boto3** | AWS SDK for Python | Talks to AWS S3 (file storage) and AWS Textract (OCR) | Can't upload files or extract text from PDFs |
| **LangGraph** | Graph-based orchestration framework (from LangChain team) | Defines the extraction pipeline as a two-node workflow (extract → validate) | Would need to manually chain the LLM call and validation logic |
| **pypdf** | PDF parsing library | Validates uploaded PDFs and counts pages before processing | Can't verify file is actually a valid PDF |
| **passlib + bcrypt** | Password hashing library | Hashes patient passwords for the registration system | Passwords stored in plaintext — security vulnerability |
| **python-multipart** | Multipart form parser | Handles file upload parsing in FastAPI | File uploads won't work (FastAPI can't parse multipart forms) |
| **psycopg2-binary** | PostgreSQL adapter for Python | The actual driver that SQLAlchemy uses to talk to Postgres | SQLAlchemy can't connect to PostgreSQL |
| **httpx** | Async HTTP client | Required by the OpenAI SDK for making HTTP requests | OpenAI API calls fail |

### Frontend

| Library | What it is | Why it's here | What breaks without it |
|---------|-----------|---------------|----------------------|
| **React 19** | UI component library | Renders the entire dashboard UI | No frontend |
| **Vite** | Build tool and dev server | Bundles TypeScript/React code, provides hot-reload in development | Can't build or serve the frontend |
| **TypeScript** | Typed JavaScript | Catches type errors at compile time; makes code self-documenting | No type safety; harder to maintain |
| **react-router-dom** | Client-side routing | Enables navigation between Dashboard (`/`) and Document Detail (`/documents/:id`) pages | Can't navigate between pages |

### Infrastructure

| Technology | What it is | Why it's here |
|-----------|-----------|---------------|
| **Docker + Docker Compose** | Container orchestration | Runs all 7 services (Postgres, Redis, Neo4j, Backend, Worker, Frontend, Nginx) with one command |
| **PostgreSQL 15** | Relational database | Stores patient accounts and document metadata (including the JSONB structured data) |
| **Neo4j 5.15** | Graph database | Stores the medical knowledge graph — nodes (Patient, Encounter, Claim, Condition, Hospital) and relationships between them |
| **Redis 7** | In-memory key-value store | Message broker for Celery task queue |
| **Nginx** | Reverse proxy | Routes requests to either backend or frontend based on URL path |

